content:
Author unknown.
An all together fantastic trip involving two breaking-in&rsquo;s (don&rsquo;t panic&hellip;someone only climbed through the windows of a) the caravan and b) the mini bus.) the rather unfair exclusion of a very authentic and rustic looking ice pick, much to someone&rsquo;s utter dismay&hellip; &hellip;the full novelty of the mini bus roof rack (inclusive of very useful ladder up the back of the bus to enable a quick and easy transfer of self from very back of bus to front windscreen preferably of the same mini bus from which you started from&hellip;if not then the fast flowing motorway below&hellip;) motorcyclists also had the extra bonus of the back door opening as they would try and pass us on the motorway&hellip;
There was also the amazing discovery of a &lsquo;bouncy castle&rsquo; in someone&rsquo;s, rather foolishly, unguarded back garden&hellip;and the shock discovery of a whole live frog!!!! And the same person who discovered all these amazing things also cunningly managed to turn (by a feat of PURE skill) everything that she touched black and glittery&hellip; The caravans were fantastic, apart from the cleaning that had to be done the next morning&hellip;
Although the Saturday&rsquo;s climbing weather was well behaved, giving an excellent days climbing Sunday was impeded by rain, which also led to fabulous &lsquo;sudden&rsquo; decisions to have &lsquo;rests&rsquo; during climbs. Coupled with people&rsquo;s sudden and unexplained attraction to the ground. The followed by an even more spectacular climb back up a steep, muddy, bramble lined walk to the mini bus. The keys to which had gone on a little adventure all of their own&hellip; Everyone made it back in one piece, and no one had left and bags anywhere (especially in Beit Quad&hellip;)
